The 5th Conference on Analysis, Probability and Mathematical Physics on  Fractals was held at the Cornell University Mathematics Department from  June 11-15, 2014. Each of the 5 days of the meeting was structured in four parts:

half-hour talks in the mornings by leading researchers in the field to describe recent important advances;
mini-courses  in the early afternoons to enable advanced undergraduates, graduate  students, and researchers from related fields to learn some of the  foundations of the area and discuss important open problems;
elaborations: half-hour elaborations of the 30-minute main talks, following our tradition (since Fractals 2), are intended to be informal talks, discussions, question-and-answer sessions for people particularly interested in a given subject (the time slots were intermingled to allow interested people to ask questions in all sessions);
and 20  minute talks in the late afternoons to allow more of attendees to present their research. There were a diverse group of about  a hundred participants from many countries and four different  continents, ranging from undergraduate students to established  researches.



The topics of this conference included many studies  in which the underlying space is fractal, and the subjects included the  analogs of differential equations, random processes and models of  physical interactions taking place on these fractal spaces. Due to the  pioneering work of Barlow, Perkins, Bass, Kusuoka, Zhou and Kigami there  is a well-established, rigorous mathematical framework for discussing  such problems. These conferences have been held every 3 years starting  in 2002. They have been instrumental in fostering the development of  these areas in recent years, both through the participant's research and  through mentoring younger researchers. All these 5 conferences in this  series have had a major impact in the development of these reasearch fields by  bringing together leading contributors, young researchers and  mathematicians in related disciplines to learn about recent work and  plan joint projects. The 5th conference has continued in this tradition,  and was perhaps the most successful of the five.

A significant  part of the proposed conference was the mini-courses, which were  directed primarily at the training of future mathematicians. A large  number of junior researchers, including minorities, members of  underrepresented groups and undergraduate students from both the Cornell  and University of Connecticut REU programs, benefited from these  courses. Theoretical physicists attended and gave talks, so the  conference helped to foster the growing interactions between the  mathematics and physics communities with interests in these areas. There  are many important scientific questions involving modeling physical  systems on fractal spaces. This conference helped inform the physics  community of the infrastructure being developed by mathematicians, and  gave mathematicians interesting feedback on the interests and questions  of other scientists. A large number of cooperative projects are underway  that resulted from the information and ideas disseminated at the  conference.

